{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01NXGjHdcJHqMBAXMMAqQTgS","type":"tool_result","content":"660\t  - [x] Programmatically invoke `duplo fix \"sample bug\"`. Mock the investigator LLM call and capture the prompt.\n661\t  - [x] Assert: the captured investigator prompt contains the counter-example reference's path or notes content, framed under an explicit \"AVOID\" label.\n662\t  - [x] If the spec has counter-example SOURCES (URLs with `role: counter-example`), assert: the URL appears in the investigator prompt under the same AVOID framing, AND `fetch_site` was NOT called against that URL.\n663\t\n664\t- [x] Run the full test suite and confirm Phase 5 closes cleanly\n665\t  - [x] Execute `pytest -x` against the duplo repo.\n666\t  - [x] Assert: all pre-existing tests still pass; all seven new Phase 5 integration tests pass.\n667\t  - [x] If any test fails, the task fails and mcloop will retry. The retry should investigate the failure (read pytest output, identify the failing assertion, locate the responsible code, fix it). Phase 5 is not complete until this task passes.\n668\t\n669\t## Followup: bugs surfaced during the manual run of the URL-only scenario\n670\t\n671\tThe manual run of the URL-only scenario (against numi.app) before this rewrite surfaced real bugs. Queued here so they don't get lost.\n672\t\n673\t- [x] Fix planner output wrapped in markdown code fences\n674\t  - [x] When duplo's planner generates a PLAN.md via `claude -p` and the LLM returns the markdown wrapped in triple-backtick fences, duplo writes the wrapped text verbatim. The resulting file is unparseable by mcloop because the H1 heading is buried inside a code fence.\n675\t  - [x] Fix: in `duplo/planner.py` (or wherever the planner output is written), strip leading/trailing fences before writing. Use the existing `strip_fences` helper from `duplo/parsing.py` if it covers this case; if not, extend it.\n676\t  - [x] Tests: planner output containing a fenced markdown block is written without the fences. Output without fences is written unchanged. Output with `~~~` fences is also handled.\n677\t\n678\t- [x] Fix planner placing feature tasks under `## Bugs` heading\n679\t  - [x] The Phase 1 PLAN.md generated during the manual run had its feature implementation tasks placed UNDER the `## Bugs` heading instead of as the plan body. `## Bugs` should be empty initially. Feature tasks should be at the top level under the phase H1 heading.\n680\t  - [x] Investigate `duplo/planner.py` (or saver.py's `save_plan`) to find where the structure is being assembled wrong.\n681\t  - [x] Fix: ensure the planner's output has the correct structure: H1 phase heading, then feature tasks at top level, then `## Bugs` heading at the end with no tasks below it.\n682\t  - [x] Tests: a generated PLAN.md has feature tasks at top level under the H1 heading. The `## Bugs` heading is present but contains no tasks. Mcloop's parser correctly identifies the feature tasks as Phase 1 work, not as bugs.\n683\t\n684\t- [x] Fix `derive_app_name` not writing `product_name` to product.json\n685\t  - [x] During the manual run, the PLAN.md heading correctly read `# numi — Phase 1: Scaffold` (so the app name was derived as \"numi\" somewhere), but `.duplo/product.json` had `product_name: \"\"` (empty string).\n686\t  - [x] Investigate `duplo/orchestrator.py:derive_app_name` and its callers. Either the function isn't writing `product_name` (only writing `app_name`), or `product.json` is initialized with empty `product_name` and never updated.\n687\t  - [x] Fix: ensure `product.json` ends up with `product_name` populated to the same value used in the PLAN.md heading. Backward-compat: if `product.json` already has a non-empty `product_name` (user-edited), do not overwrite.\n688\t  - [x] Tests: after `_subsequent_run`, `product.json:product_name` matches the value used in PLAN.md's H1 heading. User-edited `product_name` survives a subsequent run.\n689\t\n690\t- [x] Fix `frame_describer` parse-error on every video frame\n691\t  - [x] During the manual run, all 17 video frames extracted from a demo video were stored with `state: \"unknown\"`, `detail: \"parse error\"` in `.duplo/duplo.json` `frame_descriptions`. The frame describer's LLM call is returning output that the parser cannot handle. Pre-existing behavior, not caused by Phase 5, but surfaced clearly during Phase 5 verification.\n692\t  - [x] Investigate `duplo/frame_describer.py`. Capture a real LLM response sample and inspect what the parser is choking on.\n693\t  - [x] Fix: make the parser tolerant of common LLM output variations: strip code fences, strip leading/trailing prose, parse the first valid JSON object found. Alternatively, tighten the prompt to demand strict JSON output.\n694\t  - [x] Tests: parser handles JSON wrapped in fences; parser handles JSON preceded by prose; parser handles JSON with trailing whitespace; parser returns a useful error message when the LLM truly returned something unparseable.\n695\t\n696\t- [x] Investigate why AUTO-GENERATED design block was not written to SPEC.md during the manual URL-only run\n697\t  - [x] During the manual run, design extraction appears to have completed (no error logged), but SPEC.md ended the run with no `## Design` section and no AUTO-GENERATED block.\n698\t  - [x] Investigate: in `_subsequent_run`, after `extract_design` is called, what happens with the result? Is `format_design_block(design)` producing a non-empty string? Is `update_design_autogen` being invoked? Is its result being written back? Add a diagnostic at each step if the chain breaks.\n699\t  - [x] Fix: ensure the write-back happens reliably whenever `extract_design` returns a non-empty result. The `test_autogen_design_block_present_skips_vision` test will catch this regression once the bug is fixed.\n700\t  - [x] Note: this bug may be entangled with the frame_describer bug — if the design extractor receives only \"unknown\" frame descriptions, it may produce empty or trivial output that legitimately doesn't merit a write-back. Investigate the relationship.\n701\t\n702\t---\n703\t\n704\t# Phase 6: Drafter and duplo init\n705\t\n706\tAdds duplo init and the full spec-drafter that creates SPEC.md entries from URL scrapes, prose descriptions, and existing reference files (via Vision). Updates the migration message from Phase 4 to reference duplo init.\n707\t\n708\tDesign references: DRAFTER-design.md (authoritative for spec_writer.py extensions), INIT-design.md (authoritative for duplo init UX and behavior). When a task description and the design doc disagree, the design doc wins; flag the discrepancy for resolution rather than silently picking one interpretation.\n709\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"1d5a0bb2-dafd-476c-8755-3edf150f4691","uuid":"49554f13-fa0d-4886-ac30-a72ded743d9c","timestamp":"2026-05-16T13:30:48.695Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/Users/mhcoen/proj/duplo/PLAN.md","content":"  - [x] Programmatically invoke `duplo fix \"sample bug\"`. Mock the investigator LLM call and capture the prompt.\n  - [x] Assert: the captured investigator prompt contains the counter-example reference's path or notes content, framed under an explicit \"AVOID\" label.\n  - [x] If the spec has counter-example SOURCES (URLs with `role: counter-example`), assert: the URL appears in the investigator prompt under the same AVOID framing, AND `fetch_site` was NOT called against that URL.\n\n- [x] Run the full test suite and confirm Phase 5 closes cleanly\n  - [x] Execute `pytest -x` against the duplo repo.\n  - [x] Assert: all pre-existing tests still pass; all seven new Phase 5 integration tests pass.\n  - [x] If any test fails, the task fails and mcloop will retry. The retry should investigate the failure (read pytest output, identify the failing assertion, locate the responsible code, fix it). Phase 5 is not complete until this task passes.\n\n## Followup: bugs surfaced during the manual run of the URL-only scenario\n\nThe manual run of the URL-only scenario (against numi.app) before this rewrite surfaced real bugs. Queued here so they don't get lost.\n\n- [x] Fix planner output wrapped in markdown code fences\n  - [x] When duplo's planner generates a PLAN.md via `claude -p` and the LLM returns the markdown wrapped in triple-backtick fences, duplo writes the wrapped text verbatim. The resulting file is unparseable by mcloop because the H1 heading is buried inside a code fence.\n  - [x] Fix: in `duplo/planner.py` (or wherever the planner output is written), strip leading/trailing fences before writing. Use the existing `strip_fences` helper from `duplo/parsing.py` if it covers this case; if not, extend it.\n  - [x] Tests: planner output containing a fenced markdown block is written without the fences. Output without fences is written unchanged. Output with `~~~` fences is also handled.\n\n- [x] Fix planner placing feature tasks under `## Bugs` heading\n  - [x] The Phase 1 PLAN.md generated during the manual run had its feature implementation tasks placed UNDER the `## Bugs` heading instead of as the plan body. `## Bugs` should be empty initially. Feature tasks should be at the top level under the phase H1 heading.\n  - [x] Investigate `duplo/planner.py` (or saver.py's `save_plan`) to find where the structure is being assembled wrong.\n  - [x] Fix: ensure the planner's output has the correct structure: H1 phase heading, then feature tasks at top level, then `## Bugs` heading at the end with no tasks below it.\n  - [x] Tests: a generated PLAN.md has feature tasks at top level under the H1 heading. The `## Bugs` heading is present but contains no tasks. Mcloop's parser correctly identifies the feature tasks as Phase 1 work, not as bugs.\n\n- [x] Fix `derive_app_name` not writing `product_name` to product.json\n  - [x] During the manual run, the PLAN.md heading correctly read `# numi — Phase 1: Scaffold` (so the app name was derived as \"numi\" somewhere), but `.duplo/product.json` had `product_name: \"\"` (empty string).\n  - [x] Investigate `duplo/orchestrator.py:derive_app_name` and its callers. Either the function isn't writing `product_name` (only writing `app_name`), or `product.json` is initialized with empty `product_name` and never updated.\n  - [x] Fix: ensure `product.json` ends up with `product_name` populated to the same value used in the PLAN.md heading. Backward-compat: if `product.json` already has a non-empty `product_name` (user-edited), do not overwrite.\n  - [x] Tests: after `_subsequent_run`, `product.json:product_name` matches the value used in PLAN.md's H1 heading. User-edited `product_name` survives a subsequent run.\n\n- [x] Fix `frame_describer` parse-error on every video frame\n  - [x] During the manual run, all 17 video frames extracted from a demo video were stored with `state: \"unknown\"`, `detail: \"parse error\"` in `.duplo/duplo.json` `frame_descriptions`. The frame describer's LLM call is returning output that the parser cannot handle. Pre-existing behavior, not caused by Phase 5, but surfaced clearly during Phase 5 verification.\n  - [x] Investigate `duplo/frame_describer.py`. Capture a real LLM response sample and inspect what the parser is choking on.\n  - [x] Fix: make the parser tolerant of common LLM output variations: strip code fences, strip leading/trailing prose, parse the first valid JSON object found. Alternatively, tighten the prompt to demand strict JSON output.\n  - [x] Tests: parser handles JSON wrapped in fences; parser handles JSON preceded by prose; parser handles JSON with trailing whitespace; parser returns a useful error message when the LLM truly returned something unparseable.\n\n- [x] Investigate why AUTO-GENERATED design block was not written to SPEC.md during the manual URL-only run\n  - [x] During the manual run, design extraction appears to have completed (no error logged), but SPEC.md ended the run with no `## Design` section and no AUTO-GENERATED block.\n  - [x] Investigate: in `_subsequent_run`, after `extract_design` is called, what happens with the result? Is `format_design_block(design)` producing a non-empty string? Is `update_design_autogen` being invoked? Is its result being written back? Add a diagnostic at each step if the chain breaks.\n  - [x] Fix: ensure the write-back happens reliably whenever `extract_design` returns a non-empty result. The `test_autogen_design_block_present_skips_vision` test will catch this regression once the bug is fixed.\n  - [x] Note: this bug may be entangled with the frame_describer bug — if the design extractor receives only \"unknown\" frame descriptions, it may produce empty or trivial output that legitimately doesn't merit a write-back. Investigate the relationship.\n\n---\n\n# Phase 6: Drafter and duplo init\n\nAdds duplo init and the full spec-drafter that creates SPEC.md entries from URL scrapes, prose descriptions, and existing reference files (via Vision). Updates the migration message from Phase 4 to reference duplo init.\n\nDesign references: DRAFTER-design.md (authoritative for spec_writer.py extensions), INIT-design.md (authoritative for duplo init UX and behavior). When a task description and the design doc disagree, the design doc wins; flag the discrepancy for resolution rather than silently picking one interpretation.\n","numLines":50,"startLine":660,"totalLines":1120}}}
